# Essential to know
- Use `.map()` to convert arrays to JSX.
- Returns a new array of elements.
- Always add a unique `key` prop.

---

# Rendering Lists in React

## The map() Method

Use JavaScript's `map()` to transform arrays into JSX:

```jsx
const items = ['Apple', 'Banana', 'Cherry'];

function FruitList() {
  return (
    <ul>
      {items.map(item => <li>{item}</li>)}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

## Why map()?

- Transforms each array element into JSX
- Returns a new array of elements
- Perfect for dynamic lists

lessons.codeExample:
function TodoList() {
  const todos = [
    { id: 1, text: 'Learn React' },
    { id: 2, text: 'Build an app' },
    { id: 3, text: 'Deploy it' },
  ];

  return (
    <ul>
      {todos.map(todo => (
        <li key={todo.id}>{todo.text}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}

function FilteredList() {
  const products = [
    { id: 1, name: 'Apple', price: 1.5, inStock: true },
    { id: 2, name: 'Banana', price: 0.5, inStock: true },
    { id: 3, name: 'Cherry', price: 3.0, inStock: false },
  ];

  const availableProducts = products
    .filter(p => p.inStock)
    .sort((a, b) => a.price - b.price);

  return (
    <ul>
      {availableProducts.map(product => (
        <li key={product.id}>
          {product.name} - ${product.price}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}

